WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.360
5 years ago, I decided to learn more about two exciting frameworks that I kept hearing

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:19.160
about more and more often, everywhere really, in bars, restaurants. It got really spooky.

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:25.680
The first is the R Tidyverse from Hadley's and Garrett's great book, Alpha Data Science.

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:31.320
Some of you might have heard of it, maybe. And the second one is the Kaggle Machine Learning

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:37.200
and Data Science Platform. And little did I know at the time that a combination of those

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:44.080
frameworks would transform my career and open up a whole new world of exciting challenges.

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:49.520
And much like for our Dragon Ball friends there, this fusion really boosted my power

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:57.240
level. So today, I would like to show you how the Kaggle community can help you to grow,

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:02.840
to learn, and to inspire others. And whether you're a regular in Kaggle, have only ever

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:08.440
dipped your toes into the community, or have never heard of it at all, I hope that my talk

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:13.839
and my story will inspire you to make the most out of the amazing opportunities that

00:01:13.839 --> 00:01:19.519
the Kaggle community provides. And that, in turn, you will then share your great ideas

00:01:19.519 --> 00:01:27.360
and creativity with the rest of us. Now, that sounds great, you might say. I have a very

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:36.760
small question, though. What is Kaggle? Well, I'm glad you asked. Kaggle.com was launched

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:42.400
13 years ago as a website for machine learning competitions. And that means that the goal

00:01:42.559 --> 00:01:47.199
is to build competitive predictive models on a specific machine learning problem,

00:01:47.199 --> 00:01:52.559
with the best models in the end scoring highest on an objective leaderboard. And while competitions

00:01:52.559 --> 00:01:57.440
remain one of the main cornerstones, today, Kaggle covers many key aspects of the data

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:04.400
science landscape. Users can upload and curate their own data sets. Lively discussion forums

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:10.399
host many conversations about machine learning and data science. And Kagglers can build, run,

00:02:10.399 --> 00:02:16.479
and publish their own notebooks directly on the site. And there's so much to learn here,

00:02:16.479 --> 00:02:21.279
so much to discover. But I also realize that all these possibilities can be a little bit

00:02:21.839 --> 00:02:28.399
confusing, right? Maybe intimidating when you're joining the site at first. And I get it. I really

00:02:28.399 --> 00:02:34.080
do. When I joined Kaggle back in the day, I felt the same. I felt a little bit hesitant when I saw

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:40.160
all these smart people and their clever ideas. So much so, in fact, that I decided to join up

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:47.759
anonymously under the pseudonym Heads or Tails. Nobody knew who I really was. And that helped to

00:02:47.759 --> 00:02:52.080
alleviate much of the pressure that I would have otherwise put myself under when it comes to

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:58.720
actively participating in the community. So with this little trick, I felt free to work my regular

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:05.600
job during the day and be on Kaggle in my secret identity in the evenings and, well, nights.

00:03:06.559 --> 00:03:12.720
And but what I quickly realized is that much like the R community, the Kaggle community was

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:17.919
exceptionally welcoming and supportive of its new members. And it remains so to this day.

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:25.440
The other trick that helped me was at first to only focus on one aspect of Kaggle rather than

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:31.759
trying to do everything at once. And in my case, I gravitated towards the notebooks. You see,

00:03:32.479 --> 00:03:37.600
I'm a very visual person and my academic background had trained me to write coherent

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:44.160
reports. And my goal on Kaggle was to learn new tools and new methods. And I always learn best

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:50.639
when I can apply these new tools on a practical problem. So it came natural to me to start

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:54.720
writing and publishing notebooks to learn and to share what I learned with others.

00:03:55.199 --> 00:04:00.960
And so today my talk will be evolving around the notebooks. But much of what I'm telling you can

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:07.039
be translated to Kaggle's other aspects as well, like discussions or competitions or also courses

00:04:07.039 --> 00:04:13.279
which might be more relevant for you and your goals. And all these aspects are representative

00:04:13.279 --> 00:04:18.720
of Kaggle as a whole. And in turn, they also contain smaller areas that are representative

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:27.040
of them. So in a sense, much like a cauliflower, this is a fractal approach and a fractal talk

00:04:27.839 --> 00:04:32.959
in which I would like to show you that I can be less than just a one-dimensional speaker.

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:41.679
I take that. So I started learning the R-Tidyverse and to write Kaggle notebooks to practice what I

00:04:41.679 --> 00:04:47.920
had learned. And I also started reading the notebooks that other people had written. And

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:53.839
the notebooks that other people were putting out. And that really exploded my horizons.

