00:10:36.719 --> 00:10:42.880
notebooks and writing quite a few myself, I would like to share with you what Kaggle taught me on

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:49.840
how to write a great notebook, right? So here are a few tips that will be illustrated by different

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:57.520
hidden gems. So first of all, you want to introduce your work to capture your reader's attention and

00:10:57.520 --> 00:11:03.520
draw them into your analysis. A couple of topical images or illustrations go always well

00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:09.039
with a few opening paragraphs that explain the goals, the context, and set the scene for what's

00:11:09.039 --> 00:11:15.200
to follow. So like Laura here, you could use an image of cocoa beans to lead into your flavorful

00:11:15.200 --> 00:11:22.799
analysis of chocolate taste ratings. Explaining your methodology will help your reader to follow

00:11:22.799 --> 00:11:27.840
your analysis through its various steps. And this can be part of your introduction. And you can even

00:11:27.840 --> 00:11:33.840
go as far as Ram Shankar did and build a flow chart out of little pictograms that explain the

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:38.960
different steps of your analysis. And this is really some next level methodology communication

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:47.599
right there. Great visuals, of course. They are at the heart of many fantastic notebooks.

00:11:47.599 --> 00:11:54.320
And whether it's for exploration or for communication, you want your data visualizations

00:11:54.320 --> 00:12:01.760
to be clear and accessible in communicating the insights that you derived. And that can mean simple

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:08.479
visuals, but it can also mean complex but well designed. So in this example here, Daniel

